{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":453064,"duration_api_ms":442415,"num_turns":18,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"0e7cdbb1-4c0e-4028-aa3b-0e19c5869fdd","total_cost_usd":1.2631304999999997,"usage":{"input_tokens":17,"cache_creation_input_tokens":53002,"cache_read_input_tokens":735265,"output_tokens":12066,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":53002,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":17,"outputTokens":12066,"cacheReadInputTokens":735265,"cacheCreationInputTokens":53002,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":1.00063,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000},"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":202,"outputTokens":10487,"cacheReadInputTokens":1197485,"cacheCreationInputTokens":72092,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.26250049999999997,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Reviewed all changes across `src/adapters/fs.rs` and `src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs`. All three issues are addressed with correct implementations:\n\n**Issue 1 (Struct drift):** Solved via round-trip tests (`start_journal_details_round_trips_with_model_render`, `completion_journal_details_round_trips_with_model_render`) that render JSON through the model's canonical function, parse through the fs adapter's struct, then assert re-rendered output is identical. Compile errors on render function signature changes force test updates, and the re-render equality check catches any missing fields. Both `render()` methods in the fs structs delegate directly to the model's render functions, providing an additional compile-time coupling.\n\n**Issue 2 (Runless-to-named):** The runless match path now requires `started_at` to match exactly, preventing wrong-entry backfill. Happy path tested by `runless_start_completed_with_named_run_id`; rejection path tested by `runless_match_rejected_when_started_at_mismatches`. The existing `completion_with_conflicting_plan_hash_rejects_runless_match` test was correctly updated to use matching `started_at` so it still exercises the plan_hash conflict path.\n\n**Issue 3 (plan_hash auto-population):** Auto-population was moved from service.rs to fs.rs `record_task_run_start`, applied ONLY on new entry creation. Existing rows (backfill and finalization paths) are explicitly excluded with documented rationale — snapshot.plan_hash can advance after the original attempt started, so stamping the current hash would mislabel entries. Tests cover: auto-population on new entries, no mislabeling of legacy rows, no conflicts on replay after plan evolution.\n\nAll 683 tests pass. No critical bugs found. One minor amendment proposed regarding test robustness for the struct-drift protection.","amendments":[{"body":"The round-trip struct-drift tests (`start_journal_details_round_trips_with_model_render` and `completion_journal_details_round_trips_with_model_render`) populate all optional fields with `Some` values, which correctly catches missing fields via the re-render equality assertion. However, neither `StartJournalDetails` nor `CompletionJournalDetails` uses `#[serde(deny_unknown_fields)]`. This means that in production (outside the test), if a new field is added to the model's render function but not to the fs adapter's parsing struct, parsing will silently succeed and `merge()` will silently discard the unrecognized field — the exact failure mode Issue 1 describes. The round-trip test catches this in CI, but adding `#[serde(deny_unknown_fields)]` to both `StartJournalDetails` and `CompletionJournalDetails` would also catch it at runtime, providing defense-in-depth. If forward-compatibility with newer journal formats is a concern, this could be gated behind a test-only assertion instead.","rationale":"The round-trip tests are the primary guard but only run in CI. Adding `deny_unknown_fields` would make the struct drift a runtime error rather than a silent data-loss scenario, aligning with the acceptance criterion that drift 'cannot' happen without a failure. The cost is low (two derive attributes) and the forward-compatibility concern can be addressed by handling the deserialization error gracefully in the `parse()` methods (which already return `Option` and silently swallow errors via `.ok()`)."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"f43e8c36-303f-4043-ab70-11cffeb5b4ac"}
